6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"KuCoin follows standard 8-hour funding intervals common to most CEXs, calculating rates based on premium/discount to spot and interest rate differentials. Hyperliquid's 1-hour intervals provide more frequent arbitrage opportunities but require faster position management. KuCoin's funding rates tend to be more stable due to deeper liquidity, while Hyperliquid's shorter intervals can create more volatile rate swings. Both use similar premium-based calculations, but Hyperliquid's on-chain transparency allows real-time rate verification."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lc",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Hyperliquid's 1-hour funding intervals create 8x more arbitrage opportunities than KuCoin's 8-hour cycles. However, KuCoin's deeper liquidity and altcoin variety may offer more diverse rate spreads across different perpetuals."},{"question":"How do the funding rate calculations differ between platforms?","answer":"Both use premium-based calculations, but Hyperliquid's on-chain order book provides transparent rate computation. KuCoin's rates are typically more stable due to deeper liquidity pools, while Hyperliquid can see sharper rate movements."},{"question":"Which platform is better for institutional funding rate strategies?","answer":"KuCoin offers better institutional features like API trading bots and cross-margin capabilities. Hyperliquid provides on-chain transparency but lacks institutional custody solutions and has USDC-only settlement limitations."},{"question":"What are the main risks for funding rate arbitrage on each platform?","answer":"KuCoin faces regulatory scrutiny and potential liquidity gaps during volatile periods. Hyperliquid carries smart contract risk and single-chain dependency, though its shorter funding intervals reduce exposure time per position."}]}]
